00:00:20.632 --> 00:00:22.090
PROFESSOR: We want
to start talking

00:00:22.090 --> 00:00:26.960
about a seemingly
simple but very complex

00:00:26.960 --> 00:00:30.620
system in physics, the
harmonic oscillator.

00:00:30.620 --> 00:00:35.400
So the next part is actually
due to Professor Vladan Vuletic,

00:00:35.400 --> 00:00:40.320
who worked out the
topic very nicely about,

00:00:40.320 --> 00:00:43.100
how precisely can you
measure frequencies?

00:00:47.350 --> 00:00:49.860
And I don't need to
remind you that some

00:00:49.860 --> 00:00:53.580
of the most accurate
measurements in all of physics

00:00:53.580 --> 00:00:56.660
are done by measuring frequency.

00:00:56.660 --> 00:01:00.420
It's actually a kind
of unwritten rule.

00:01:00.420 --> 00:01:02.370
If you want to measure
something precisely,

00:01:02.370 --> 00:01:06.360
make sure that you find a
way that this quantity can

00:01:06.360 --> 00:01:08.620
be measured in a
frequency measurement.

00:01:08.620 --> 00:01:11.270
Because frequencies,
that's what we

00:01:11.270 --> 00:01:14.660
can measure-- with synthesizers,
with clocks, and such.

00:01:14.660 --> 00:01:16.990
So therefore, the question,
how precisely can you

00:01:16.990 --> 00:01:20.270
measure frequency, is a
question which is actually

00:01:20.270 --> 00:01:22.065
relevant for all
precision measurements.

00:01:25.890 --> 00:01:28.860
Well, we know we
have Fourier theorem.

00:01:28.860 --> 00:01:38.600
If you have an oscillator which
oscillates for a time delta t,

00:01:38.600 --> 00:01:42.370
we have the Fourier
theorem which

00:01:42.370 --> 00:01:50.450
says we have a finite width of
the frequency spectrum delta

00:01:50.450 --> 00:02:00.150
omega, or there is the spread
of frequency components involved

00:02:00.150 --> 00:02:06.750
in such a way that delta
omega times delta t

00:02:06.750 --> 00:02:10.660
is large or equal than 1/2.

00:02:10.660 --> 00:02:15.370
The case of 1/2 is realized
for Gaussian wave packets.

00:02:15.370 --> 00:02:24.580
And of course, Fourier theorem
should also-- this Fourier

00:02:24.580 --> 00:02:30.035
limit should remind you of
Heisenberg's uncertainty

00:02:30.035 --> 00:02:30.535
relation.

00:02:37.190 --> 00:02:40.375
Of course, Fourier limit and
Heisenberg uncertainty relation

00:02:40.375 --> 00:02:43.550
are related because what
Heisenberg expressed

00:02:43.550 --> 00:02:46.252
turns out to be simply
the limit due to the wave

00:02:46.252 --> 00:02:46.960
nature of matter.

00:02:52.740 --> 00:02:53.290
OK.

00:02:53.290 --> 00:02:55.640
So I brought the
clicker because I

00:02:55.640 --> 00:03:00.720
want you to think about some
seemingly simple question.

00:03:00.720 --> 00:03:12.650
The first question is whether
the uncertainty delta omega

00:03:12.650 --> 00:03:18.630
times delta t larger than
1/2, does this uncertainty

00:03:18.630 --> 00:03:22.790
hold for purely
classical systems?

00:03:28.110 --> 00:03:33.464
So think about it and
answer in your clicker.

00:03:33.464 --> 00:03:36.760
A is 1 and B-- oh,
I should say that.

00:03:50.500 --> 00:03:54.190
So we now assume we have a
purely classical-- you can even

00:03:54.190 --> 00:03:57.120
think a mechanical,
large mechanical object,

00:03:57.120 --> 00:03:59.630
purely classical
harmonic oscillator.

00:03:59.630 --> 00:04:02.350
You can observe it
for time delta t,

00:04:02.350 --> 00:04:04.590
or it oscillates
for time delta t.

00:04:04.590 --> 00:04:08.540
Can you determine its
frequency better then

00:04:08.540 --> 00:04:10.650
this uncertainty suggests?

00:04:14.600 --> 00:04:16.050
19, 20.

00:04:16.050 --> 00:04:17.990
Just make up your mind.

00:04:17.990 --> 00:04:20.959
As I said, your
responses are not

00:04:20.959 --> 00:04:25.130
recorded, so nothing to risk.

00:04:25.130 --> 00:04:25.630
OK.

00:04:29.980 --> 00:04:32.610
Yes.

00:04:32.610 --> 00:04:39.820
OK, the majority gave
the right answer.

00:04:43.880 --> 00:04:51.790
The situation is that
the answer is yes,

00:04:51.790 --> 00:04:57.790
if you have a good
signal to noise ratio.

00:05:04.270 --> 00:05:12.940
So what happens is, if you--
we have to bring in the fact

00:05:12.940 --> 00:05:15.600
that we have noise.

00:05:15.600 --> 00:05:21.780
So if you have a wave formed,
there may be noise around it.

00:05:21.780 --> 00:05:33.680
And if you look at the spectrum,
the spectral components

00:05:33.680 --> 00:05:35.520
have a certain width.

00:05:35.520 --> 00:05:39.980
And this width, delta omega,
is given by Fourier's theorem

00:05:39.980 --> 00:05:44.490
by the time delta t you
had for observation.

00:05:44.490 --> 00:05:51.230
But as you see, you can
determine the center

00:05:51.230 --> 00:06:01.250
of this spectral peak with an
accuracy delta omega, which

00:06:01.250 --> 00:06:05.210
may be much better than the
[? width ?] delta omega.

00:06:05.210 --> 00:06:07.190
And the rule of
thumb is that you

00:06:07.190 --> 00:06:11.630
can split a line by your
signal to noise ratio.

00:06:11.630 --> 00:06:15.600
So typically, the
accuracy of a measurement

00:06:15.600 --> 00:06:19.640
is whatever the width
of the spectrum is,

00:06:19.640 --> 00:06:22.740
and then you can split the line
by the signal to noise ratio.

00:06:31.860 --> 00:06:35.635
This is called
splitting the line.

00:06:41.600 --> 00:06:48.486
Factor of hundred is usually
regarded as straightforward.

00:06:51.600 --> 00:06:57.060
But if you want to go
to larger than that,

00:06:57.060 --> 00:07:00.300
it becomes a challenge.

00:07:00.300 --> 00:07:03.440
Because even if you have a very
good signal to noise ratio,

00:07:03.440 --> 00:07:06.550
you really have to make sure
that you know the line shape,

00:07:06.550 --> 00:07:09.000
that you know that it is,
for instance, symmetric,

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:12.150
and that the line center
of the observed shape

00:07:12.150 --> 00:07:14.640
is really where
the frequency is.

00:07:20.760 --> 00:07:23.080
I will give you some
examples in a few moments.

00:07:23.080 --> 00:07:29.720
But before that, I would like
to continue our discussion

00:07:29.720 --> 00:07:32.700
whether we can measure
the angle of frequency

00:07:32.700 --> 00:07:35.970
to better than the
Heisenberg limit

00:07:35.970 --> 00:07:39.340
in case of a
quantum-mechanical oscillator.

00:07:39.340 --> 00:07:49.830
So the question is, can
you measure the frequency

00:07:49.830 --> 00:08:01.340
of a quantum-mechanical harmonic
oscillator in a time delta t

00:08:01.340 --> 00:08:11.695
to an accuracy which is better
than the limit of Heisenberg's

00:08:11.695 --> 00:08:12.195
uncertainty?

00:08:21.380 --> 00:08:22.570
OK, your vote, please.

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:49.850
All right.

00:08:55.120 --> 00:08:56.220
OK.

00:08:56.220 --> 00:08:59.010
Why don't we hold
that for a second

00:08:59.010 --> 00:09:06.150
and proceed to the next
question which is the same?

00:09:06.150 --> 00:09:09.650
But now, instead of a
quantum-mechanical harmonic

00:09:09.650 --> 00:09:12.710
oscillator, we take
something we are

00:09:12.710 --> 00:09:17.300
very familiar with--
an optical laser--

00:09:17.300 --> 00:09:24.190
and we observe a laser pulse
lasting a duration delta t.

00:09:27.150 --> 00:09:30.500
So same situation, but
instead of observing

00:09:30.500 --> 00:09:33.260
a quantum-mechanical
harmonic oscillator,

00:09:33.260 --> 00:09:36.890
we observe a laser pulse.

00:09:36.890 --> 00:09:41.160
For the laser, can we
measure the frequency

00:09:41.160 --> 00:09:46.950
of the optical radiation better
than this equality tells us?

00:10:04.120 --> 00:10:04.620
OK.

00:10:04.620 --> 00:10:07.780
At least people are consistent
because the first thing

00:10:07.780 --> 00:10:11.210
I wanted to tell you is
that, is the laser actually

00:10:11.210 --> 00:10:15.700
a classical harmonic oscillator
or quantum harmonic oscillator?

00:10:15.700 --> 00:10:18.990
Well, we use a
quantum description

00:10:18.990 --> 00:10:23.120
of light and the laser is
the population of photons

00:10:23.120 --> 00:10:26.070
in the single note of the
electromagnetic field.

00:10:26.070 --> 00:10:29.340
So in that sense, the
laser is fully quantum.

00:10:29.340 --> 00:10:31.430
But in the limit that
the laser is many,

00:10:31.430 --> 00:10:35.300
many photons-- and some of you
know about coherence states.

00:10:35.300 --> 00:10:39.890
If there's a coherent state
with a large photon number,

00:10:39.890 --> 00:10:41.910
the laser is actually
the classical limit

00:10:41.910 --> 00:10:44.280
of an electromagnetic field.

00:10:44.280 --> 00:10:47.300
So maybe that tells
me that the answers

00:10:47.300 --> 00:10:51.590
to questions 2 and question 3
should probably be the same.

00:10:51.590 --> 00:10:53.620
And I want to say more about it.

00:10:53.620 --> 00:10:55.680
So at least in this class,
you were consistent.

00:10:55.680 --> 00:10:57.390
I have often seen
a big discrepancy

00:10:57.390 --> 00:10:59.550
in the answers between
question 2 and question 3.

00:11:02.930 --> 00:11:09.830
OK, so the answer is yes.

00:11:09.830 --> 00:11:13.510
So both for the laser-- I
first explain the laser to you,

00:11:13.510 --> 00:11:17.027
and then we go back to the
pure quantum system, thing

00:11:17.027 --> 00:11:18.360
has actually certain subtleties.

00:11:20.890 --> 00:11:25.130
But for the laser,
it is obvious,

00:11:25.130 --> 00:11:28.180
at least if I tell you
how I want to measure it,

00:11:28.180 --> 00:11:32.440
because I can take the
laser and create a beat

00:11:32.440 --> 00:11:44.210
note with another
very stable laser.

00:11:44.210 --> 00:11:46.460
And I record this beat
note on a photodiode.

00:11:51.230 --> 00:11:54.145
I can realize by making
this other laser,

00:11:54.145 --> 00:11:57.340
the local oscillator
stronger and stronger,

00:11:57.340 --> 00:11:59.390
I can create a
beat note which is

00:11:59.390 --> 00:12:01.860
larger and larger
and corresponds

00:12:01.860 --> 00:12:04.400
to a macroscopic
electric current which

00:12:04.400 --> 00:12:06.280
can be measured with
very high precision.

00:12:10.060 --> 00:12:13.600
So you can realize an
arbitrarily high signal

00:12:13.600 --> 00:12:22.000
to noise ratio by using a
strong local oscillator.

00:12:27.120 --> 00:12:30.580
And then you can actually
say the photocurrent, which

00:12:30.580 --> 00:12:34.020
comes out of the
photodiode, is actually--

00:12:34.020 --> 00:12:37.440
you can regard this microscopic
current as purely classical.

00:12:37.440 --> 00:12:40.440
And then of course, the answer
to the first question applies.

00:12:43.520 --> 00:12:47.740
So that takes care of question
3 by mapping it actually

00:12:47.740 --> 00:12:49.540
on question 2.

00:12:49.540 --> 00:12:51.920
But now by saying
that the laser also

00:12:51.920 --> 00:12:55.420
has a quantum-mechanical limit
and I'm not changing anything,

00:12:55.420 --> 00:12:58.390
we realize that probably
the answer to question 2

00:12:58.390 --> 00:13:00.750
should also be yes.

00:13:00.750 --> 00:13:08.160
So let's, therefore,
ask our self, what

00:13:08.160 --> 00:13:13.530
is the situation when the
Heisenberg uncertainty

00:13:13.530 --> 00:13:14.325
relation applies?

00:13:25.550 --> 00:13:32.440
Well, one is we have
to be really careful.

00:13:32.440 --> 00:13:37.070
It predicts the outcome
of a single measurement

00:13:37.070 --> 00:13:39.806
on a single quantum system.

00:13:39.806 --> 00:13:41.290
Let me write that down.

00:13:44.180 --> 00:13:46.230
Or if the Heisenberg
uncertainty relation

00:13:46.230 --> 00:13:49.670
sets a limit, how well we
prepare a quantum system.

00:13:49.670 --> 00:13:53.132
It's about a single
quantum system,

00:13:53.132 --> 00:13:54.840
and then we perform
a single measurement.

00:14:17.110 --> 00:14:23.680
So in a sense, if
we would say all

00:14:23.680 --> 00:14:30.690
you have is a single photon,
which is a very special quantum

00:14:30.690 --> 00:14:31.480
system.

00:14:31.480 --> 00:14:35.740
You have a single
photon and you measure

00:14:35.740 --> 00:14:39.010
the frequency of the
photon only once.

00:14:39.010 --> 00:14:43.520
Then your will find the limit,
which is the Heisenberg limit.

00:14:43.520 --> 00:14:48.040
You cannot, with a single
measurement on a single photon,

00:14:48.040 --> 00:14:57.540
determine the accuracy of the
frequency better than this.

00:14:57.540 --> 00:15:00.890
And of course, you can
get higher accuracy

00:15:00.890 --> 00:15:12.400
by doing repeated measurements
or by using many photons.

00:15:21.470 --> 00:15:27.630
We talk about it more in 8.422,
but I just want to remind you,

00:15:27.630 --> 00:15:32.500
if you have n
uncorrelated photons.

00:15:37.670 --> 00:15:40.810
In other words, we
perform n measurements

00:15:40.810 --> 00:15:45.530
on n different objects, then
the signal to noise ratio

00:15:45.530 --> 00:15:51.510
is-- just by Poisson
distribution, square root n.

00:15:51.510 --> 00:15:54.790
And therefore, the
resolution for the frequency

00:15:54.790 --> 00:15:59.970
of the photons is better than
the Heisenberg or the Fourier

00:15:59.970 --> 00:16:02.300
limit by 1 over
the square root n.

00:16:06.730 --> 00:16:09.520
Some of you-- and actually,
in Professor Vuletic's group,

00:16:09.520 --> 00:16:14.810
there is research on it that
if you have correlated-- well,

00:16:14.810 --> 00:16:16.500
in his case, correlated atoms.

00:16:16.500 --> 00:16:21.090
But if you had
correlated photons,

00:16:21.090 --> 00:16:24.090
then you can even do better.

00:16:24.090 --> 00:16:29.340
You can reach what is sometimes
called the Heisenberg limit

00:16:29.340 --> 00:16:32.260
where you are better
than the limitation

00:16:32.260 --> 00:16:34.950
given by Fourier's theorem or
by the Heisenberg uncertainty

00:16:34.950 --> 00:16:37.390
relation by a factor of 1/n.

00:17:13.869 --> 00:17:14.369
OK.

00:17:14.369 --> 00:17:23.200
So as far as the question 2
where the quantum harmonic

00:17:23.200 --> 00:17:33.540
oscillator is
concerned, we would

00:17:33.540 --> 00:17:46.860
say the answer is
yes, if you have

00:17:46.860 --> 00:17:57.785
is single photon at
frequency omega 0,

00:17:57.785 --> 00:18:08.360
which interacts with the
quantum harmonic oscillator

00:18:08.360 --> 00:18:09.650
at frequency omega 0.

00:18:09.650 --> 00:18:16.710
However, the answer
would, even in that case,

00:18:16.710 --> 00:18:23.270
be no if you have
harmonic oscillator levels

00:18:23.270 --> 00:18:29.740
and you take a photon and
by a nonlinear process

00:18:29.740 --> 00:18:32.250
excite the n-th level.

00:18:32.250 --> 00:18:33.995
So you have a single photon now.

00:18:38.620 --> 00:18:44.850
You can resolve the energy
delta E of this level.

00:18:44.850 --> 00:18:47.960
A single photon,
a single quantum

00:18:47.960 --> 00:18:55.382
object, you can
define the energy--

00:18:55.382 --> 00:18:57.090
that's Heisenberg's
uncertainty relation.

00:18:57.090 --> 00:19:01.160
The energy is determined
to that precision.

00:19:04.140 --> 00:19:17.810
But your frequency omega
of the optical pulse

00:19:17.810 --> 00:19:22.230
is n times omega 0
using nonlinear process.

00:19:22.230 --> 00:19:26.170
And then you can determine
the frequency of the harmonic

00:19:26.170 --> 00:19:28.770
oscillator, even
for a single quantum

00:19:28.770 --> 00:19:38.450
system and a single
photon with a precision

00:19:38.450 --> 00:19:41.510
which is 1/n times better.

00:19:41.510 --> 00:19:44.470
So you have to be
also careful, but I

00:19:44.470 --> 00:19:46.120
don't want to beat
it to death now,

00:19:46.120 --> 00:19:50.010
to distinguish between the
accuracy at which Heisenberg's

00:19:50.010 --> 00:19:52.520
uncertainty relation
maybe limits

00:19:52.520 --> 00:19:54.530
the measurement of
an energy level.

00:19:54.530 --> 00:19:57.340
And how this is related
to the frequency

00:19:57.340 --> 00:19:58.800
of the harmonic oscillator.

00:19:58.800 --> 00:20:02.100
And by going sort of
immediately to the n-th level,

00:20:02.100 --> 00:20:04.721
you can, of course, measure
the distance between two levels

00:20:04.721 --> 00:20:07.220
more accurately because you
have increased your [INAUDIBLE].

00:20:14.770 --> 00:20:15.826
Any questions?

00:20:15.826 --> 00:20:17.700
AUDIENCE: Sorry, I just
got a little confused

00:20:17.700 --> 00:20:22.630
about when yes means one
thing and no means one thing.

00:20:22.630 --> 00:20:26.642
So you're saying that you can
beat the uncertainty relation

00:20:26.642 --> 00:20:31.362
in questions 1, 2, and 3
if you can put it in a way

00:20:31.362 --> 00:20:34.210
where you get good
signal to noise?

00:20:34.210 --> 00:20:37.240
PROFESSOR: OK, I gave you--
sorry for being complicated,

00:20:37.240 --> 00:20:38.760
but the physics is complicated.

00:20:38.760 --> 00:20:40.260
I try to give it to you
in different layers.

00:20:40.260 --> 00:20:41.843
I first looked at
the classical limit,

00:20:41.843 --> 00:20:43.190
which is pretty clear-cut.

00:20:43.190 --> 00:20:44.820
Then, I used a laser.

00:20:44.820 --> 00:20:46.500
The laser has a
classical limit where

00:20:46.500 --> 00:20:48.700
the answer is the same as
in the classical limit.

00:20:48.700 --> 00:20:50.610
But then we can talk
also in the laser

00:20:50.610 --> 00:20:52.680
in the limit of single photons.

00:20:52.680 --> 00:20:55.490
And then I said, OK, the
single photon interacting

00:20:55.490 --> 00:20:57.460
with a single
quantum system, this

00:20:57.460 --> 00:20:59.200
is really when it is quantum.

00:20:59.200 --> 00:21:01.900
And if you have a two-level
system and you [INAUDIBLE]

00:21:01.900 --> 00:21:04.040
it with a single
photon, then you

00:21:04.040 --> 00:21:08.690
can make a measurement which
is limited by this inequality.

00:21:08.690 --> 00:21:10.870
But then I said
there is a caveat.

00:21:10.870 --> 00:21:24.000
And this is if you bring
in a nonlinear process.

00:21:31.460 --> 00:21:35.630
So if your bring in a nonlinear
process, we can go up n steps.

00:21:35.630 --> 00:21:38.366
We can drive-- we can,
by some nonlinearity,

00:21:38.366 --> 00:21:40.490
drive the harmonic oscillator
from the ground state

00:21:40.490 --> 00:21:41.900
to the n state.

00:21:41.900 --> 00:21:44.600
Then, everything we have
said about a single photon

00:21:44.600 --> 00:21:46.740
and the measurement of
the resonance and such

00:21:46.740 --> 00:21:48.860
applies to this photon.

00:21:48.860 --> 00:21:51.650
But the energy level of
the harmonic oscillator

00:21:51.650 --> 00:21:53.880
has now been measured with
n times higher precision

00:21:53.880 --> 00:21:56.340
because we can divide by n.

00:21:56.340 --> 00:22:02.290
So the answer is yes, yes, then
quantum mechanics we cannot

00:22:02.290 --> 00:22:05.500
make it more accurate
unless we pull some tricks.

00:22:05.500 --> 00:22:08.000
And nonlinear physics
would be a trick.

00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:10.860
So in general, the
situation where you really

00:22:10.860 --> 00:22:15.470
limit it by this inequality
where your precision is limited

00:22:15.470 --> 00:22:20.040
would really only apply to a
single photon, a single quantum

00:22:20.040 --> 00:22:23.750
physics, and linear physics.

